column1: The set comes with three bags: One for the structure and cockpit, and two for each of the pods. the build is decent but nothing amazing. A little bit of repetitive building for detail on the pods, but overall, a fair build. One thing to note is that for a thirty dollar set, a lot of stickers are used. There are three on each of the pods, and

column1: The built Podracer looks overall quite nice. It has two flexible wires that act as the cables reaching the cockpit to the pods. The main cockpit can hold either a short minifig like Anakin
column2: or one with medium/ normal legs. There is also a handle so you can swoosh it around. The absolute worst thing about the sets is that to hold the pods to the cockpit, really nice clear technic pieces are used. But they use tan pins to hold the clear pieces together, and it looks just, so noticeable. They could have&nbsp
column3: used grey at least, which would have looked a little better, but overall, a fair build.

column1: All in all, this is a nice set. nothing over the top, as there isn'

,TRUE,4,4,4,2,4 lego_collector_123","2020-01-26T11:18:51.087Z","Now that's what i call podracing!","

The last Lego Podracer set was released in 2011 and I'
column2: m glad to get a remake. This time it was included in a line of 20th anniversary Star Wars sets to celebrate 20 years of Lego Star Wars. Each 20th anniversary set includes a special edition minifigure, which is a rerelease of a classic Lego Star Wars character. The set feels overpriced but looks very movie accurate, so I approach this set with high hopes.&nbsp

column1: Anakin Skywalker: This version of Anakin comes with a helmet and googles instead of hair. Unfortunately, the helmet piece is lacking in detail
column2: in the movie it is grey with red patterning, here however it is plain brown. His appropriate expressions shows a concentrating frown on one side and a cheerful grin on the other. The torso print looks great on the front and back and it features a belt over a simple tan shirt. He comes with plain short tan legs, and carries a wrench.&nbsp
s hair piece looks fantastic. It&#39
column3: s a exclusive mould which shows her hair braided into a bun and hanging down the back. I like her main expression
column4: a battle ready grimace, but I think the blank look on the reverse of her head looks boring and uncharacteristic. Her torso print looks great. This figure uses the relatively new medium legs which are perfect here. For accessories she carries a standard blaster.&nbsp

column1: 20th Anniversary X-Wing pilot Luke Skywalker: I love the idea of the 20th anniversary minifigures. Each figure come on a stand which has the characters name and the 20th anniversary logo printed on it. The stands connect together for display. Luke&#39
column2: s classic helmet is iconic, and I appreciate his classic face print on a yellow head. His torso shows the original print on the front but has the 20th anniversary logo on the back, an idea which I don&#39
column3: t mind, because it both preserves the value of the original figures, and looks good on display. His legs are unprinted and his lightsaber looks great. &nbsp

column1: Two fins act as mudguards to the cockpit section of this set which are angled elegantly. A blue sticker details the otherwise grey front. There is enough space for a figure to stand or sit in the cockpit which features a small windscreen and two handlebars. The rear of the cockpit has more nice angles and a mix of blue and grey parts. The cockpit is decorated with 8 stickers which I find irritating and unnecessary although they do add to the look of the set. I love the whole cockpit design although I'
column2: d rather fewer stickers. Gun metal grey pipes lead from the cockpit to the engine pods.&nbsp

column1: I love the engine pods of this model. The yellow air scoops have sticker details and can be angled in and out. The detail continues down the engine with blue curved parts used on the front and sides to great effect. Dark orange pieces along with silver cones, detail the engines which end in grey boosters. My favorite part of the pods is the underside which uses repurposed copper Uruk Hai swords to show texture. The light purple transparent lightning bolt pieces used to represent energy arcing between the two pods also looks fantastic.
Unfortunately, the stand/handle is only partially transparent as some of the pieces don&#39
column2: t come in transparent clear, tan and light grey are used instead. I don&#39
column3: t mind this compromise and I think the final look is good. The stand also plays well, offering an easy grip for what is otherwise a difficult set to play with.

column1: The line of Star Wars 20th anniversary sets released in 2019 has some good sets and this is one of my favorites. The combination of a screen accurate podracer, two nice minifigures, and the exclusive 20th anniversary X-Wing pilot Luke makes this a good set for kids and collectors alike. Although I'
column2: d rather a larger set that includes two or more podracers, the choice to make the set more affordable by only including one is understandable. The only major downside of the set is the price. $45 aud for a set this size feels excessive, and the piece count of 279 doesn&#39
column3: t make the price any more reasonable. I think $35 - $40 would be a good price for this set.&nbsp

,TRUE,4,3,3,4,4 Struhadlo","2020-04-08T18:56:27.607Z","I did not see this coming","

I have a confession to make. I only bought this set to complete my 20th Anniversary collection. And I must say I was foolish to anticipate this to be a bad set. It has few building problems and an enormous amount of stickers for such a small set, but otherwise this is a fantastic set.
No problem here. 30$ for 279 is fair and after building the set I must say that I am surprised they did not push this to be a 35$ or even 40$.

column2: ..an exact replica of the original Lego Star Wars minifig.&quot
column3: which is not true. The minifig comes with a humongous 20th Anniversary print on the back and the hilt is the same modern silver mold and not the original chrome one. Furthermore, the white west has an orange accent as the colour underneath bleeds through. I am little disappointed by the lack of quality of the printing job here. Other than that it is practically identical old minifig with single face, yellow head and old print. It comes on a stand which you can connect to other 20th Anniversary minifigs.

column1: <li>Anakin Skywalker. A decent minifig with print detailed enough on the torso and the back. No leg nor arm printing. The head has two expressions and I must say they are rather accurate. What I mean is that the face looks somewhat recognizable. The legs are obviously the small ones. Annie comes with a wrench and a pilot helmet with goggles. The goggles do not make him look like he is squinting which is usually the problem with Lego goggles.&nbsp

column2: Amidala. The most interesting minifig in this set with a modest print again on the back and the torso without any printing done on the legs nor arms. There are two expressions as usual. The regular face looks like a regular stock Lego female face, but the angry is reminiscent to Padm&eacute
column3: to some degree. The hair mold is what makes this minifig desirable&nbsp
column4: as it is unique to this set I belive. The legs are poseable as with the regular Lego legs, but they are middle-sized. Strangely, she is armed with a blaster gun.

column1: The minifig selection feels somewhat weak in this set but that is due to the lack of any fighters or troopers here I feel like. I would say that there was no better way to do the minifig selection for this set without forcing in some characters which would not make too much sense.
column3: switch Padm&eacute
column4: for a Tusken Raider, but that is just me I guess.

column1: I hold nothing but admiration for the designer of this set as I do not think doing so is an easy task at all. But still, the designers of this set did provide us with a sturdy and well-detailed Podracer. The Podracer is surprisingly big and takes a lot of space. It is far bigger than the boxset suggests. The vehicle does wiggle a wee bit if you swoosh
column2: with it, but the wiggle does not ruin the experience. Most of the parts hold where they should hold and nothing falls apart. The level of detailing here is fantastic! There is a heavy emphasis on stickers and I think there is 14 of them in total. And most of them are small and quite difficult to apply. The engines look very convincing and you can actually move few parts on them so simulate their different states during the race.&nbsp

column1: The construction is held together with bunch of clear technic pieces and this is probably the best way about it. You can take them off the build and leave it in the movie-accurate state, but then it will be very difficult to play with. The Podracer uses a lot of interesting pieces in its construction and even few orange-goldish Uruk-Hai
column2: machetes. If you do not mind the stickers then the building experience is quite fun as you see the vehicle build in front of you. There are few actions that are redundant as you build the same thing over and over again, but those are just small parts of the engines and it is done fairly quickly. Other than that this is one of more enjoyable builds to put together.

column1: There are no classic play features such as stud shooters in this set but that does not render this set uninteresting for kids. The handle allows for an easy action and there are still 3 minifigs to play with. AS already mentioned, there are few winglets on the sides of the engines and you can take different parts off to simulate damage.
All things considered, this is a great looking vehicle. Even if
column2: you are not into podracing you might still consider buying this as I am not into that too and I still enjoy this set very much. Keep in mind the unholy mound of stickers, but other than that&nbsp
column3: I think the design and the amount of detail with quite unique minifigs make for a fantastic set. I wholeheartedly recommend this to both collectors looking for a displayable set and kids alike, or anyone who buys Lego to play with.&nbsp

The stand can connect with other 20th anniversary characters and the tile is printed saying &ldquo
column9: . Our second minifigure is young boy Anakin which he comes with a wrench, has a brown helmet with gray googles. He has front and back printing on the torso and small legs. column9: s Podracer features a lot of features like a handle to make it fly like it did in the Mos Espa Podrace.
